Ah, you’re right about the IDs, given that Jupyter output cells aren’t themselves framed (like Colab output cells are).

My first thought was to try something like the following—

```html
<script>
(function() {
  const frame = document.createElement("iframe");
  const url = new URL("/", window.location);
  url.port = %PORT%;
  frame.src = url;
  const me = document.currentScript;
  me.parentNode.insertBefore(frame, me);
})();
</script>
```

—but Jupyter rehydrates scripts by appending them to `document.head`, so
`document.currentScript` actually refers to the wrong element here, and
this doesn’t work.

Perhaps we could fall back to a simple nonce-based solution? Something
like:

```python
import cgi
import json
import random

frame_id = "tensorboard-frame-{:08x}".format(random.randrange(0, 1 << 64))
shell = """
<iframe id="%HTML_ID%" width="100%" height="%HEIGHT%"></iframe>
<script>
(function() {
  const frame = document.getElementById(%JSON_ID%);
  const url = new URL("/", window.location);
  url.port = %PORT%;
  frame.src = url;
})()
</script>
"""
replacements = [
    ("%HTML_ID%", cgi.escape(frame_id, quote=True)),
    ("%JSON_ID%", json.dumps(frame_id)),
    ("%PORT%", "%d" % port),
    ("%HEIGHT%", "%d" % height),
]
for (k, v) in replacements:
  shell = shell.replace(k, v)
IPython.display.HTML(shell)
```

