It also appears that changing the URL by hand causes a page reload, even if you're just modifying the `resultStatus` param.  This was one of the advantages of the hash URLs, since that gave us the ability to decide when to reload the page.  Is there a way to control that with `history'?  I know that you can listen for `history` changes with:

    history.listen((location) => {
        console.log(`You changed the page to: ${location.pathname}`)
    })

But this is the opposite issue of too much page reloading.  Perhaps `react-router-dom` has a way to control that.  Or perhaps we want to actually still use some params after the `#` like flitering to prevent page reload?  

I wonder if you may have to use a listener on `history` like:

    history.listen((location) => {
            console.log(`You changed the page to: ${location.pathname}`)
        })

A big part of using those event listeners was handling when someone changed the URL by hand.  Like changing the `resultStatus` property in this branch will reload the page.

