Latest iteration: User subclass doesn't need to set any attributes themselves. They just need to define what attributes from their constructor can get re-specified. Then, they just pass these through as kwargs to the `BaseTrainer.restore`.

```python
class MyTrainerSubclass(BaseTrainer):
    def restore(cls, path, my_arg, ...):
        return super().restore(path, my_arg=my_arg, ...)
        # No more setting things afterwards.
```

There really isn't anything wrong with comparing to 0.  People get into trouble when they write code like this though
```
void foo(double a, double b) 
{
    double val = a + b + b; // might end up being equal to just a if b is less than a*epsilon.
    double val2 = val - 2*b; // And say 2*b > a*epsilon, then this will make val2 != val.  So now val2 != a.
    if (val2 == a) 
    {
         // this might never happen depending on the value of b.  This foo function is just fundamentally numerically unsound.
    }
}
```

But that isn't the kind of situation here. And in general you definitely do not want to use the machine epsilon as a proxy for "it's zero".  For double it's only about 2e-16.  But values of double like 1e-30 are perfectly legit and meaningful.  The machine epsilon is really just a convenient way to ask "how much precision is in the mantissa?".  It's not telling us how much precision we have left in the exponent.

So for example, if you wanted to compute the ratio of two lengths `a/b` you want to do just `a/b`.  And if `b` can be 0 you have to decide what you want `a/0` to mean.  So 
```
if (b == 0) return whatever
else return a/b;
```
is what you do.  If instead it was this
```
if (b < std::numeric_limits<double>::epsilon()) return whatever
else return a/b;
```
then the wrong value would be obtained for values like 1e-20/1e-19.  Which should be 10.0, not `whatever`.

In the above foo example, you would use the epsilon in a setup like this
```
void foo(double a, double b) 
{
    double val = a + b + b;
    double val2 = val - 2*b;
    if (std::abs(val2 - a) <= std::numeric_limits<double>::epsilon() * 2*b) 
    {
         // This will execute.
    }
}
```

